# 6.

# We put the attributes of the iris flowers in X and the names in y
X <- iris[,-5]
y <- iris[,5]

# 7.

# We will now scale the features (centré-réduit)
X_scaled = scale(X,scale = TRUE, center=TRUE
)

# 8.

# Covariance-matrix :

X_scaled_cov = cov(X_scaled)
X_scaled_cov
##              sepal_length sepal_width petal_length petal_width
## sepal_length    1.0000000  -0.1093692    0.8717542   0.8179536
## sepal_width    -0.1093692   1.0000000   -0.4205161  -0.3565441
## petal_length    0.8717542  -0.4205161    1.0000000   0.9627571
## petal_width     0.8179536  -0.3565441    0.9627571   1.0000000
# 9.

# Eigen decomposition of the cov matrix :
eigen = eigen(X_scaled_cov)
eigen_vectors = eigen[1]
eigen_values = eigen[2]
eigen_vectors
## $values
## [1] 2.91081808 0.92122093 0.14735328 0.02060771
eigen_values
## $vectors
##            [,1]        [,2]       [,3]       [,4]
## [1,]  0.5223716 -0.37231836  0.7210168  0.2619956
## [2,] -0.2633549 -0.92555649 -0.2420329 -0.1241348
## [3,]  0.5812540 -0.02109478 -0.1408923 -0.8011543
## [4,]  0.5656110 -0.06541577 -0.6338014  0.5235463
# We see that the largest eigen value is 2.92, and it's the variance of comp 1 (so Sepal Length)
# The elements for these eigenvectors will be the coefficients of the principal components.
# (Ce sont les lambda i)

# 10.

# Eigen decomposition of correlation matrix based on scaled data
X__scaled_cor = cor(X_scaled)
eigen(X__scaled_cor)

# 11.

# Eigen decomposition of correlation matrix
X_cor = cor(X)
eigen(X_cor)
## eigen() decomposition
## $values
## [1] 2.91081808 0.92122093 0.14735328 0.02060771
## 
## $vectors
##            [,1]        [,2]       [,3]       [,4]
## [1,]  0.5223716 -0.37231836  0.7210168  0.2619956
## [2,] -0.2633549 -0.92555649 -0.2420329 -0.1241348
## [3,]  0.5812540 -0.02109478 -0.1408923 -0.8011543
## [4,]  0.5656110 -0.06541577 -0.6338014  0.5235463
# We obtain the same results with the previous question, because 
# the correlation matrix is the normalised covariance matrix
# (On voit donc que même après avoir centré-réduit les valeurs, les lambda i restent les mêmes)

# 12. 

eigen_values = eigen(X_cor)$values
eigen_vectors = eigen(X_cor)$vectors

# Taux d'inertie

indvar_pc1 = eigen_values[1]/sum(eigen_values)
indvar_pc2 = eigen_values[2]/sum(eigen_values)
indvar_pc3 = eigen_values[3]/sum(eigen_values)
indvar_pc4 = eigen_values[4]/sum(eigen_values)

# Taux d'inertie cumulés

cumvar_pc1 = (eigen_values[1])/sum(eigen_values)
cumvar_pc2 = (eigen_values[1]+eigen_values[2])/sum(eigen_values)
cumvar_pc3 = (eigen_values[1]+eigen_values[2]+eigen_values[3])/sum(eigen_values)
cumvar_pc4 = (eigen_values[1]+eigen_values[2]+eigen_values[3]+eigen_values[4])/sum(eigen_values)

# 13 .

# Another way to plot the scree plot :

indvar_pc = c(indvar_pc1, indvar_pc2, indvar_pc3, indvar_pc4)
indvar_pc
## [1] 0.727704521 0.230305233 0.036838320 0.005151927
plot(indvar_pc,type='b')

# 14.

# Projection matrix :

A = cbind(eigen_vectors[,1],eigen_vectors[,2])
A
##            [,1]        [,2]
## [1,]  0.5223716 -0.37231836
## [2,] -0.2633549 -0.92555649
## [3,]  0.5812540 -0.02109478
## [4,]  0.5656110 -0.06541577
# 15.

# Projection of the observations onto the new subspace

Y = X_scaled %*% A

# 16.

# Plotting the observations on the new feature space

plot(Y,xlab='PC1',ylab='PC2')

# 17.

# Add some colors to it :)

col = c(1:150)

for (i in 1:length(col)){
  if (y[i] ==  'setosa') col[i] = 'red'
  if (y[i] ==  'versicolor') col[i] = 'blue'
  if (y[i] ==  'virginica') col[i] = 'green'
}

plot(Y,xlab='PC1',ylab='PC2',col=col)
